---
title: Loaders
---

<div class="row u-mb-5">
  <div class="small-12 columns">
    <h1>Loaders</h1>
    <p>By default loaders work on a white background but offer classes for both grey and blue backgrounds. Loaders will occupy the width and height of it's parent container, and the loader will automatically be centered.</p>

  </div>
</div>

<div class="row">
  <div class="small-12 columns">
    <h2>Loader</h2>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row u-mb-5">
  <div class="small-6 columns">
  	<div class="Loader"></div>
  </div>
  <div class="small-6 columns">
    <div class="Loader Loader--small"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row u-mb-7">
   <div class="small-12 columns">
    <pre>
      <code><%= display_code('
<div class="Loader"></div>
<div class="Loader Loader--small"></div>') %></code>
    </pre>
   </div>
</div>

<div class="row u-mb-5">
  <div class="small-12 columns">
    <h2>Basic Loader</h2>
    <p>Basic loaders are great for inline usage. An example of a basic loader being used correctly is on the <a href="https://cloud.digitalocean.com/support/suggestions" target="_blank">Lifeboat's</a> help article search input.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row u-mb-5">
  <div class="small-12 columns">
    <div class="Loader--basic u-mr-2"></div>
    <div class="Loader--basic Loader--blue"></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="row u-mb-7">
   <div class="small-12 columns">
    <pre>
      <code><%= display_code('
<div class="Loader--basic"></div>
<div class="Loader--basic Loader--blue"></div>') %></code>
    </pre>
   </div>
</div>